function minimumTeachings(n, languages, friendships) {
    const languageUsers = {};
    const unconnectedUsers = new Set();

    friendsLoop: for (const [u, v] of friendships) {
        canCommunicate = false;

        for (const lang of languages[u - 1]) {
            if (languages[v - 1].includes(lang)) {
                canCommunicate = true;
                continue friendsLoop;
            }
        }

        if (!canCommunicate) {
            unconnectedUsers.add(u);
            unconnectedUsers.add(v);
        }
    }

    let res = unconnectedUsers.size;
    for (let i = 1; i <= n; ++i) {
        let cnt = 0;
        for (const user of unconnectedUsers) {
            if (!languages[user - 1].includes(i)) {
                cnt++;
            }
        }
        res = Math.min(res, cnt);
    }

    return res;
}
```

    1. Initialize two data structures: a dictionary `language_users` to store the users for each language and a set `unconnected_users` to store users who cannot communicate with each other.
2. Iterate through the `friendships` array, and for each pair of users (u, v), check if they can communicate (common language). If they cannot, add both users to the `unconnected_users` set.
3. Initialize the result `res` with the size of the `unconnected_users` set.
4. Iterate through all languages from 1 to n, and for each language, count the number of users who don't know that language in the `unconnected_users` set. Update the result with the minimum count found.
5. Return the result. 

This algorithm finds the minimum number of users that need to be taught a language to ensure all friends can communicate with each other.

solutionCode.java:
    ```java
import java.util.*;

class Solution {
    public int minimumTeachings(int n, int[][] languages, int[][] friendships) {
        Map<Integer, Set<Integer>> languageUsers = new HashMap<>();
        Set<Integer> unconnectedUsers = new HashSet<>();

        for (int[] friendship : friendships) {
            int u = friendship[0], v = friendship[1];
            boolean canCommunicate = false;

            for (int lang : languages[u - 1]) {
                if (Arrays.stream(languages[v - 1]).anyMatch(x -> x == lang)) {
                    canCommunicate = true;
                    break;
                }
            }

            if (!canCommunicate) {
                unconnectedUsers.add(u);
                unconnectedUsers.add(v);
            }
        }

        int res = unconnectedUsers.size();
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; ++i) {
            int cnt = 0;
            for (int user : unconnectedUsers) {
                if (Arrays.stream(languages[user - 1]).noneMatch(x -> x == i)) {
                    cnt++;
                }
            }
            res = Math.min(res, cnt);
        }

        return res;
    }
}
```

    1. Initialize two data structures: a dictionary `language_users` to store the users for each language and a set `unconnected_users` to store users who cannot communicate with each other.
2. Iterate through the `friendships` array, and for each pair of users (u, v), check if they can communicate (common language). If they cannot, add both users to the `unconnected_users` set.
3. Initialize the result `res` with the size of the `unconnected_users` set.
4. Iterate through all languages from 1 to n, and for each language, count the number of users who don't know that language in the `unconnected_users` set. Update the result with the minimum count found.
5. Return the result. 

This algorithm finds the minimum number of users that need to be taught a language to ensure all friends can communicate with each other.
